Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stourton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from any of three places named Stourton (Staffs, Wilts, Warwicks).","2  English:  see  Sturton  .","3  English: locative name, perhaps occasionally from Storrington (Sussex), which is recorded as  <i>Storgetune</i> in 1086."],"variants":[{"name":"Storton","meanings":["English:  see  Stourton  ."]},{"name":"Sturton","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Sturton le Steeple (Notts), Great Sturton (Lincs), Sturton by Stow (Lincs), or possibly Sturton (Northumb), all of which place-names share the same etymology and early spellings as   Stratton  .","2  English:  see  Stourton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de Stourton was born in 1152, in Stourton, Wiltshire, England. She married William de Stourton in 1172, in Stourton, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents